{
  "id": "school.suffixes",
  "order": 1,
  "title": {
    "en": "Stack the Suffixes",
    "uz": "Qo'shimchalar"
  },
  "blurb": "How Uzbek builds big words from little bricks",
  "estimatedMinutes": 3,
  "sections": [
    {
      "heading": "One word, many bricks",
      "body": [
        "English builds meaning with lots of little words: *from my houses* is three of them. Uzbek builds the **same meaning inside one word**, stacking suffixes onto a root like bricks: **uylarimdan**.",
        "Each brick adds exactly one idea, and the order never changes: **root + plural + owner + case**."
      ],
      "examples": [
        {
          "uzbek": "uylarimdan",
          "english": "from my houses",
          "breakdown": [
            "uy",
            "lar",
            "im",
            "dan"
          ],
          "gloss": [
            "house",
            "plural",
            "my",
            "from"
          ]
        },
        {
          "uzbek": "kitoblarimda",
          "english": "in my books",
          "breakdown": [
            "kitob",
            "lar",
            "im",
            "da"
          ],
          "gloss": [
            "book",
            "plural",
            "my",
            "in"
          ]
        },
        {
          "uzbek": "do'stlarimga",
          "english": "to my friends",
          "breakdown": [
            "do'st",
            "lar",
            "im",
            "ga"
          ],
          "gloss": [
            "friend",
            "plural",
            "my",
            "to"
          ]
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "heading": "Watch a word grow",
      "body": [
        "Start with **ish** (work) and grow it one brick at a time. The bricks always click together the same way — Uzbek has far fewer irregular forms than English or French."
      ],
      "examples": [
        {
          "uzbek": "ishchi",
          "english": "worker",
          "breakdown": [
            "ish",
            "chi"
          ],
          "gloss": [
            "work",
            "one who does"
          ]
        },
        {
          "uzbek": "ishchilar",
          "english": "workers",
          "breakdown": [
            "ish",
            "chi",
            "lar"
          ],
          "gloss": [
            "work",
            "one who does",
            "plural"
          ]
        },
        {
          "uzbek": "ishchilarimiz",
          "english": "our workers",
          "breakdown": [
            "ish",
            "chi",
            "lar",
            "imiz"
          ],
          "gloss": [
            "work",
            "one who does",
            "plural",
            "our"
          ]
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "heading": "Why this is good news",
      "body": [
        "Long words look intimidating, but they are towers of regular bricks. Once you can peel a word into its parts, **uylarimdan** stops being noise and starts being house-s-my-from.",
        "Time to stack some bricks yourself."
      ],
      "examples": [
        {
          "uzbek": "mehmonxonadan",
          "english": "from the hotel",
          "breakdown": [
            "mehmon",
            "xona",
            "dan"
          ],
          "gloss": [
            "guest",
            "room",
            "from"
          ]
        },
        {
          "uzbek": "do'stlarimizga",
          "english": "to our friends",
          "breakdown": [
            "do'st",
            "lar",
            "imiz",
            "ga"
          ],
          "gloss": [
            "friend",
            "plural",
            "our",
            "to"
          ]
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
  "exercises": [
    {
      "id": "build-uylarim",
      "engine": "build",
      "instruction": "Stack the bricks to build “my houses”",
      "tokens": [
        "uy",
        "lar",
        "im"
      ],
      "decoys": [
        "dan",
        "chi"
      ],
      "joiner": "",
      "audioText": "uylarim",
      "translation": "uylarim — my houses"
    },
    {
      "id": "build-uylarimdan",
      "engine": "build",
      "instruction": "Now build “from my houses”",
      "tokens": [
        "uy",
        "lar",
        "im",
        "dan"
      ],
      "decoys": [
        "ga",
        "ning"
      ],
      "joiner": "",
      "audioText": "uylarimdan",
      "translation": "uylarimdan — from my houses"
    },
    {
      "id": "choice-order",
      "engine": "choice",
      "instruction": "Which order do the bricks always follow?",
      "options": [
        {
          "text": "root + plural + owner + case",
          "correct": true,
          "explain": "uy + lar + im + dan: house-s-my-from. Always this order."
        },
        {
          "text": "root + case + plural + owner",
          "explain": "The case brick always comes last."
        },
        {
          "text": "owner + root + plural + case",
          "explain": "The root always comes first — suffixes only stack on the right."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "build-ishchilar",
      "engine": "build",
      "instruction": "Build “workers”",
      "tokens": [
        "ish",
        "chi",
        "lar"
      ],
      "decoys": [
        "im",
        "da"
      ],
      "joiner": "",
      "audioText": "ishchilar",
      "translation": "ishchilar — workers"
    }
  ],
  "wrapUp": "Uzbek words are towers of bricks: root first, then plural, then who owns it, then the case. Spot the bricks and even uylarimdan reads itself."
}
